File system hierarchy in Linux:

 1. 	/  This is top level directory.
 2. /root  It is home directory for root user. (Only Admins can have access for this)
 3. /home  It is home directory for other users.
 4. /boot  It contains bootable files for linux.
 5. /etc   It contains all configuration files.
 6. /usr   By default software installed in this directory.
 7. /bin   It contains commands used by all users.
 8. /sbin  It contains commands used by super user.
 9. /dev   dev directory contains the special device files for all the devices.
10. /lib   The lib folder is a library files directory which contains all helpful library files used by the system.
11. /opt   According to the Filesystem Hierarchy Standard, /optis for “the installation of add-on application software packages”.
12. /tmp   Web browsers periodically write data to the tmp directory during page views and downloads.
13. /var   Contains variable data like system logging files

